Should 0 be a valid value for ``patience``? It looks like a reasonable value for expressing "no patience".

* If yes, I think it should be equivalent to ``patience == 1``: the training should be stopped at the end of the first epoch without improvement. 
* if no, maybe it's the case to add a check ``patience > 0`` in the constructor.

Currently, for ``patience == 0``, the stop condition is never met because in ``Trainer._should_stop_early``:
```
if self._validation_metric_decreases:
    return min(metric_history[-self._patience:]) > min(metric_history)
else:
    return max(metric_history[-self._patience:]) < max(metric_history)
```
 ``metric_history[-0:] == metric_history`` so the inequality between their min/max is always false.

### What was wrong?

see:

- https://blog.ricmoo.com/solidity-abiv2-a-foray-into-the-experimental-a6afd3d47185
- http://solidity.readthedocs.io/en/latest/abi-spec.html#handling-tuple-types

Solidity has an experimental feature that will allow *tuple* types.

> snipped below is from the linked solidity docs

```javascript
pragma solidity ^0.4.19;
pragma experimental ABIEncoderV2;

contract Test {
  struct S { uint a; uint[] b; T[] c; }
  struct T { uint x; uint y; }
  function f(S s, T t, uint a) public { }
  function g() public returns (S s, T t, uint a) {}
}
```

The code above would result in the following ABI

```javascript
[
  {
    "name": "f",
    "type": "function",
    "inputs": [
      {
        "name": "s",
        "type": "tuple",
        "components": [
          {
            "name": "a",
            "type": "uint256"
          },
          {
            "name": "b",
            "type": "uint256[]"
          },
          {
            "name": "c",
            "type": "tuple[]",
            "components": [
              {
                "name": "x",
                "type": "uint256"
              },
              {
                "name": "y",
                "type": "uint256"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "t",
        "type": "tuple",
        "components": [
          {
            "name": "x",
            "type": "uint256"
          },
          {
            "name": "y",
            "type": "uint256"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "a",
        "type": "uint256"
      }
    ],
    "outputs": []
  }
]
```



### How can it be fixed?

We should add a new `TupleEncoder` and `TupleDecoder` to handle these types.

- The `TupleEncoder` should accept an iterable of values as it's input.
- The `TupleDecoder` should return a python `tuple` of values as output.

